description:
John Linton Roberson (born in South Carolina, 1969), also known as JLRoberson, is a cartoonist, writer, editor and publisher, and former playwright, currently based in northern California.

An alumnus of DePaul University, Roberson self-published the anthology "Plastic" under his Bottomless Studio imprint from 1998-2001, in which he serialised his 252-page graphic novel "Vitriol", a black comedy. The magazine also featured work by Kamagurka & Herr Seele, and Sam Henderson, among other contributors. In 2000 he created several strips for the San Francisco web magazine "Spark-Online" under the title "Slash & Burn ".

In early 2003, he was editor, publisher, and one of 26 contributors to the comics anthology, a benefit book published in e-book format for William Messner-Loebs. The collection contains an introduction by Gary Groth as well as work by Sam Kieth, Steve Bissette, Ted Rall, Donna Barr, and P. Craig Russell. Roberson created the characters Vladrushka and Rosa & Annalisa for Fantagraphics/Eros Comix, whom he was published by 2003-2006.

In Summer 2004, he directed the premiere of his comedy "Suspension of Disbelief" in Chicago for Theatre O' Th' Absurd. According to a review of this production in the Chicago Reader, Roberson's work is "fairly obsessed with sex and death."

In 2007 he collaborated on "The Story of OH!" a parody of STORY OF O by Pauline Reage, with noted writer and sometime Terry Gilliam collaborator Charles Alverson, which was eventually published in THIS SICKNESS #1.

Since 2008, he has published, edited, and contributed 8 issues of the anthology THIS SICKNESS, featuring since 2010 his ongoing and acclaimed adaptation of Frank Wedekind's tragedy LULU. The first volume of which was published in 2013. Pages from this were exhibited in 2014 in Munich, Germany's Deutsches Theatremuseum as part of their WEDEKIND'S WORLD exhibition, and featured in the exhibition catalog. THIS SICKNESS also features his creations UNCLE CYRUS (co-created with John E. Williams), SUZY SPREADWELL, and more.

In 2013 he contributed an adaptation of Billie Holiday's "strange Fruit" to Seven Stories Press' GRAPHIC CANON Vol. 3.

He is also an occasional film critic, and appears every now and then on the DECONSTRUCTING COMICS podcast.

His work can be found at jlroberson.org.
